00:01:07.010 --> 00:01:07.593
Where are you?

00:01:07.593 --> 00:01:08.292
There you are.

00:01:08.292 --> 00:01:09.710
And Seth.

00:01:09.710 --> 00:01:11.780
And thank you all for coming.

00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:15.660
This is just, yeah, I'm
really thankful to be here.

00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:19.970
So I consider it
my life's mission

00:01:19.970 --> 00:01:25.280
to convey the urgency of
climate change through my work.

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:29.780
And to that end, I've
traveled to the polar regions

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:33.710
to capture this unfolding
story of ice melts

00:01:33.710 --> 00:01:38.030
and also to the equator to
document the rising seas that

00:01:38.030 --> 00:01:40.490
are a result of the ice melts.

00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:42.290
My drawings explore
these moments

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:46.670
of transition and
turbulence, but also

00:01:46.670 --> 00:01:51.050
tranquility in the landscape,
allowing viewers like you

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:55.550
to connect emotionally with
places that you might never

00:01:55.550 --> 00:01:57.860
have the chance
to actually visit.

00:01:57.860 --> 00:02:01.220
And I choose to convey
the beauty of these very

00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:05.570
remote regions as opposed to
the devastation in the hopes

00:02:05.570 --> 00:02:09.979
that it will inspire
people to want to help

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:11.210
protect and preserve them.

00:02:13.864 --> 00:02:16.280
To start out, I want to play
you something that I recorded

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:19.280
on the Antarctic Peninsula.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:22.370
It's a sound piece that just
premiered in my solo show

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:24.500
in Seattle, Washington.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:27.350
And I recorded it
in 2015, the winter

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:28.580
on the Antarctic Peninsula.

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:31.340
And it's a really
subtle sound, so I

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:34.100
invite you to close
your eyes or just

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:36.830
relax in whatever way
feels comfortable for you.

00:02:40.822 --> 00:02:43.816
[DRIPPING]

00:03:22.385 --> 00:03:26.940
So this sound is fondly
referred to as ice crispies,

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:30.110
as you might be able
to see if you squint.

00:03:30.110 --> 00:03:33.620
I've also heard it called bergy
seltzer and ice sizzle, which

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:37.130
I've adopted as my DJ name.

00:03:37.130 --> 00:03:42.690
But what it is is the sound of
ancient air meeting new air.

00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:45.320
It's the sound of
glacial ice melting

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:46.850
and these tiny
little air bubbles

00:03:46.850 --> 00:03:51.044
that are trapped inside
of it breaking free.

00:03:51.044 --> 00:03:52.460
And also, there's
a whirring sound

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:54.251
which you may have
heard in the background,

00:03:54.251 --> 00:03:55.790
and those are gentoo penguins.

00:03:55.790 --> 00:03:59.420
So each of these tiny
bubbles popping open

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:04.460
contains a treasure trove of
information for scientists.

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:06.020
And I recently met
with one of them

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:08.960
named John Higgins, who is
a professor of geosciences

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:10.820
at Princeton University.

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:14.810
And Higgins and his
colleagues can basically

00:04:14.810 --> 00:04:18.140
obtain the age of the ice
by studying these bubbles.

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.890
And what they do is use very
careful chemical measurements

00:04:21.890 --> 00:04:26.660
to reconstruct both the local
temperature and the ancient

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:29.930
atmosphere-- so basically, how
much carbon dioxide and methane

00:04:29.930 --> 00:04:30.710
were there--

00:04:30.710 --> 00:04:33.710
from the time when the ice
bubbles were locked inside

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:36.520
of the ice sheet.

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:38.950
So the records
from these archives

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:43.050
show, basically, how our
climate has changed in the past

00:04:43.050 --> 00:04:46.060
and what that might
portend for our future.

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:49.270
So it's important information
that we need to know.

00:04:49.270 --> 00:04:53.350
And these ice bubbles
are hundreds of thousands

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:54.670
of years old.

00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:56.650
In this picture, I'm
holding a piece of ice

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:58.272
that's a million
years old actually,

00:04:58.272 --> 00:04:59.980
and he told me it was
a million years old

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:01.021
after he handed it to me.

00:05:01.021 --> 00:05:04.060
And I was just like, oh my god,
don't know melt in my hands.

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:08.170
But actually, the results from
John's latest trip suggest he

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:12.550
collected ice that's 2 to
2 1/2 million years old.

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:15.280
And it's no news
to any of us that

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:19.300
these massive ancient
cooling systems that we

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:23.530
have at our poles that can
take millions of years to grow

00:05:23.530 --> 00:05:26.740
are rapidly melting
and that that could

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:29.952
have devastating consequences.

00:05:29.952 --> 00:05:31.660
And we know it actually
already is having

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:32.916
devastating consequences.

00:05:32.916 --> 00:05:35.320
There's all kinds
of horrible news

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:37.090
out there about climate change.

00:05:37.090 --> 00:05:38.920
There is the fact
that the past three

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:40.910
years have been the
hottest on record,

00:05:40.910 --> 00:05:42.940
or that the polar bear
population in the Arctic

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:46.032
is in rapid decline.

00:05:46.032 --> 00:05:48.490
And now we're faced with an
administration that is choosing

00:05:48.490 --> 00:05:49.600
to ignore these problems.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:52.480
I mean, even just these last
two weeks felt like apocalyptic

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:53.206
to me.

00:05:53.206 --> 00:05:55.330
I mean, I'm sure you've
heard about the earthquakes

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:57.761
and the hurricanes.

00:05:57.761 --> 00:05:59.260
And I was just in
Seattle last week,

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:01.660
and there was literally
ash falling from the sky

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:04.340
from the forest
fires in Washington.

00:06:04.340 --> 00:06:08.320
And so yeah, bad
news, but I want

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:10.810
to switch gears and tell
you about an interview

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:14.650
that I read recently where Al
Gore is talking about how we're

00:06:14.650 --> 00:06:18.070
doing in this battle against
climate change 10 years

00:06:18.070 --> 00:06:21.580
after "An Inconvenient
Truth," his first documentary.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:23.809
And what he said actually
surprised me, which

00:06:23.809 --> 00:06:25.100
is why I want to talk about it.

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:28.570
He said even though we're
behind on the scoreboard

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:33.660
when it comes to climate change,
that the momentum has shifted

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:36.290
and that we're starting to win.

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:37.820
And I think he's right.

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:40.150
I think he's onto something
because we do actually

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:42.550
have a lot to celebrate.

00:06:42.550 --> 00:06:45.010
First, of course,
there's the Paris Accord,

00:06:45.010 --> 00:06:47.860
which, even though the
US has pulled out of,

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:49.930
I actually think that's
a good thing because what

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:52.910
it did was galvanize the
whole rest of the world,

00:06:52.910 --> 00:06:55.780
including most major
US corporations,

00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:58.990
to reaffirm their
commitment to it.

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:01.390
Obama managed to permanently
ban offshore drilling

00:07:01.390 --> 00:07:04.240
in most of the Arctic
Ocean and important parts

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:06.610
of the Atlantic,
which is a huge win.

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:10.090
Iceland and Costa Rica run
on 100% renewable energy.

00:07:10.090 --> 00:07:13.300
Solar power in Chile is selling
for half the price of coal.

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:16.750
Even just in the
beginning of this year,

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:20.410
the World Economic Forum let
us know that solar and wind is

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:22.420
either the same
price or even cheaper

00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:26.170
than fossil fuels in
at least 30 countries.

00:07:26.170 --> 00:07:28.330
Nationwide, there's
a long backlog order

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:30.310
for electric cars.

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:33.130
There are real
solutions that exist,

00:07:33.130 --> 00:07:38.050
and we're already starting
to see benefits of them.

00:07:38.050 --> 00:07:41.590
And I think it's a
pretty effective tactic

00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:44.890
to emphasize the positive.

00:07:44.890 --> 00:07:49.390
A bombardment of terrifying
news which I just threw at you

00:07:49.390 --> 00:07:53.800
is paralyzing, but focusing
on the positive I think

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:55.660
is empowering.

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:58.930
So that's what I try
to do with my work--

00:07:58.930 --> 00:08:04.420
to celebrate what is still
here and to give you,

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:06.850
give viewers, the
sense that it is still

00:08:06.850 --> 00:08:09.580
possible to do
something to protect

00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:12.540
this earth that sustains us.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:16.170
So with that mission
in mind, my process

00:08:16.170 --> 00:08:18.660
always begins by
traveling to these places

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.220
at the forefront
of climate change.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:24.840
And while I'm on site, I take
thousands of photographs.

00:08:24.840 --> 00:08:26.790
And then, back in
the studio, I work

00:08:26.790 --> 00:08:29.490
from both my memory
of the experience

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:32.490
as well as the
photographs to create

00:08:32.490 --> 00:08:35.130
very large-scale compositions,
sometimes 12-feet

00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:38.190
wide like the one in this video.

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:41.520
Occasionally, I'll reinvent
the water or the sky

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.080
or maybe change the
shape of the ice

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:48.510
just a little bit to create
a balanced composition,

00:08:48.510 --> 00:08:53.370
but I'd say 90% of the time
I'm depicting the exact scene

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:56.070
that I witnessed
because I want to stay

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:58.710
true to the landscape that
actually existed at that point

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:03.452
in time, which-- just something
to take note of-- is often very

00:09:03.452 --> 00:09:04.910
different by the
time I've finished

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:07.620
the drawing several
months later.

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:10.040
So I begin with a really
simple pencil sketch

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:13.160
just so I have a few
major lines to follow,

00:09:13.160 --> 00:09:16.400
maybe the outline of the
iceberg and the horizon line.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:19.550
And then I typically jump in
pretty quickly with the color,

00:09:19.550 --> 00:09:21.740
layering pigments
onto the paper.

00:09:21.740 --> 00:09:23.945
And I smudge everything
with my fingers and palms.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:31.284
I tend to break the pastel
into these sharp shards.

00:09:31.284 --> 00:09:32.450
Oh, I work with soft pastel.

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:33.866
I should have told
you that first.

00:09:33.866 --> 00:09:36.390
It's basically like
charcoal but colors.

00:09:36.390 --> 00:09:38.400
So I'll break it into
these little sharp shards

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:40.190
that I can use to
render the finer

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:42.950
details on top of the
base layer of pigment

00:09:42.950 --> 00:09:45.180
that I've already put down.

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:48.050
And typical paper
used for soft pastel

00:09:48.050 --> 00:09:53.030
has a lot of tooth, meaning
a very textured surface

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:57.380
so that it's able to absorb
as much pigment as possible.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:00.140
I actually prefer to work on a
much smoother paper than what

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.290
most pastel artists would
want because it allows

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:05.990
me to get those finer
details without the texture

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:08.932
of the paper getting in the way.

00:10:08.932 --> 00:10:10.390
The challenge with
this, though, is

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.830
that there isn't a lot of
room for error or reworking

00:10:12.830 --> 00:10:15.400
since the paper can't
absorb so much pigment.

00:10:15.400 --> 00:10:18.580
But I honestly
enjoy this challenge

00:10:18.580 --> 00:10:21.550
because I get so lost
in the tiny details

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:23.260
that I would just
never know when

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:25.660
to stop if the
pigment and the paper

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:28.510
didn't provide those kinds
of limitations for me.

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:36.580
So I am aware that
most people can't

00:10:36.580 --> 00:10:40.940
access many of these really
remote places that I draw.

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:43.030
And so, in a lot of ways,
the environmental issues

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:48.050
there might seem remote and
disconnected from their lives.

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:50.770
So that's one
reason why I choose

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:52.930
to work on such a large scale--

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:57.790
to recreate the wonder
of witnessing an iceberg

00:10:57.790 --> 00:11:00.500
or a glacier up close.

00:11:00.500 --> 00:11:03.730
And I rely on other
specialists like scientists

00:11:03.730 --> 00:11:07.060
to make rational,
data-driven arguments

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:11.000
for why we must take action
to protect our ecosystems.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.470
But through my work, I'm
trying to make an appeal

00:11:14.470 --> 00:11:17.740
on a more elemental level.

00:11:17.740 --> 00:11:21.040
According to behavioral
psychologists,

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:25.010
much of our decision-making
comes from our emotions.

00:11:25.010 --> 00:11:28.240
And I think art has
a special ability

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:30.640
to tap into those emotions.

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:32.230
And it's not just
something I think.

00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:34.600
It's like scientifically
proven that it does.

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:36.790
So when I make
these drawings, I'm

00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:39.610
trying to create
immense images that

00:11:39.610 --> 00:11:44.320
are just overflowing with
detail that draw you in

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:46.090
and transport you.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:51.420
An author named Elaine Scarry--
she's a Harvard English

00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:55.620
professor-- wrote a book called
"On Beauty and Being Just."

00:11:55.620 --> 00:11:59.580
And in it, she talks about how--

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:01.440
she suggests, I
should say-- that when

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:04.320
we witness something
really beautiful,

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:11.190
be it a wave or a face
or a poem or a glacier,

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:15.570
that it causes in us what she
calls a radical decentering.

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:19.140
And she says, quote, "When
we see a beautiful thing,

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:21.600
our own importance
is diminished.

00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:24.510
It is not that we cease to stand
at the center of the world,

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:26.220
for we never stood there.

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:27.990
It is that we
cease to stand even

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:30.390
at the center of our own world.

00:12:30.390 --> 00:12:33.120
We willingly cede the
ground to the thing

00:12:33.120 --> 00:12:35.810
that stands before us."

00:12:35.810 --> 00:12:38.810
That is the exact
experience that I

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:43.460
hope to evoke through my work.

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:47.260
So this last school year,
I gave a series of lectures

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:48.910
at Harvard University.

00:12:48.910 --> 00:12:50.980
And in my preparation
for my talks,

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:54.220
I was scrolling through their
environmental center's website

00:12:54.220 --> 00:12:57.130
and looking at their
Climate Week from 2015.

00:12:57.130 --> 00:12:59.417
There were a bunch
of videos from it.

00:12:59.417 --> 00:13:01.750
And there was one that was
particularly compelling to me

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:03.430
that it featured
a father and son

00:13:03.430 --> 00:13:05.760
duo, Bob Keohane
on the right, who's

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:08.410
the professor of International
Affairs at Princeton

00:13:08.410 --> 00:13:11.230
University, and his son
Nat on the left, who

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:15.010
works on climate issues at the
Environmental Defense Fund.

00:13:15.010 --> 00:13:19.600
And one thing that stood out
to me that they both emphasized

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:22.240
was this notion of momentum--

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:24.520
the same momentum
that I think Al Gore

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:28.270
was talking about-- that for
there to be effective climate

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:33.580
policies, we need people and
parties from different arenas

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:37.510
to work together
in an ongoing way.

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:40.720
So that's how I
see my work fitting

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:41.830
into the bigger picture.

00:13:41.830 --> 00:13:44.620
I just want to be part
of that conversation,

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:49.030
helping to generate momentum
and unity of purpose

00:13:49.030 --> 00:13:52.690
across boundaries of
discipline and geography

00:13:52.690 --> 00:13:55.550
and political affiliation.

00:13:55.550 --> 00:13:59.800
So I guess by sharing
these moments of stillness,

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:04.870
paradoxically I'm hoping
to help generate momentum.

00:14:04.870 --> 00:14:07.030
In their talk, I
also found it really

00:14:07.030 --> 00:14:09.850
touching to see how
one Keohane had passed

00:14:09.850 --> 00:14:13.870
the torch onto the other because
I think it taps into something

00:14:13.870 --> 00:14:18.580
essential about climate change
work, which is its purview is

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:20.520
intergenerational.

00:14:20.520 --> 00:14:22.990
The work is about
passing the torch

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:26.750
and thinking ahead
several generations.

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:30.130
And I think, perhaps,
I might be particularly

00:14:30.130 --> 00:14:32.320
attuned to that dynamic
because of the debt

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:35.080
that I owe to my mother,
Rena Bass Forman.

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:37.360
She was a fine art
landscape photographer.

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:40.360
And in the last 10
years of her life,

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:43.690
her work focused on the Arctic,
and she passed that torch

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:45.940
on to me.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:49.510
My mother's love
of photography just

00:14:49.510 --> 00:14:52.330
propelled her to
the most remote,

00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:56.170
far-flung places on the planet
that she could possibly find.

00:14:56.170 --> 00:14:59.110
And my family and I were
fortunate to join and support

00:14:59.110 --> 00:15:01.840
her on those adventures
from riding camels

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:06.610
through Northern Africa to
mushing near the North Pole.

00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:09.585
She always said that she was
a polar bear in a past life,

00:15:09.585 --> 00:15:11.740
and I never doubted
that to be true.

00:15:11.740 --> 00:15:13.960
She could just
stay out for hours

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:17.320
on end with frozen eyelashes
and a giant smile on her face,

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:21.400
and the rest of my family was
like, I'm hungry and cold.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:23.530
But she just loved it.

00:15:23.530 --> 00:15:28.060
So in August of 2010
and '11, she and I

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:30.400
were planning an arctic
expedition together

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:33.610
to Greenland called
"Chasing the Light."

00:15:33.610 --> 00:15:37.750
It was to be the second-ever
arctic expedition

00:15:37.750 --> 00:15:39.790
with a mission of
creating art inspired

00:15:39.790 --> 00:15:42.490
by the dramatic geography there.

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:47.320
And the first was lead in
1869 by an American painter

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:49.180
named William Bradford.

00:15:49.180 --> 00:15:50.860
And what was unique
about that trip

00:15:50.860 --> 00:15:53.500
was that its main purpose
was art as opposed

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:55.300
to science or
exploration, which is

00:15:55.300 --> 00:15:56.980
what was happening in that day.

00:15:56.980 --> 00:15:58.720
So my mom thought,
well, wouldn't it

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:01.420
be fascinating to mirror
Bradford's journey

00:16:01.420 --> 00:16:03.730
and travel up the northwest
coast of Greenland

00:16:03.730 --> 00:16:07.200
to seek inspiration
from the same landscape

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:11.680
nearly 150 years
after Bradford had?

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:14.470
So she and I were in
the very early stages

00:16:14.470 --> 00:16:16.660
of planning this
trip when she was

00:16:16.660 --> 00:16:18.590
diagnosed with brain cancer.

00:16:18.590 --> 00:16:21.010
And the cancer
pretty quickly took

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:23.560
over her body and her
mind, and she passed away

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:25.300
six months later.

00:16:25.300 --> 00:16:28.660
But during those six
months, during those months

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:33.490
of her illness, her
dedication to the expedition

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:35.320
never wavered.

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:37.900
And so it felt
like a duty to me,

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:40.240
like I felt responsible
to carry out

00:16:40.240 --> 00:16:44.620
this mission in her honor,
which I did in August of 2012,

00:16:44.620 --> 00:16:46.960
leading a group of
artists and scholars

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:50.760
on a four-week expedition.

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:54.240
My mother's affection
for the landscape

00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:58.350
really echoed throughout my
own experience in Greenland,

00:16:58.350 --> 00:17:02.400
and I felt both
the power but also

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:05.609
the fragility of the landscape.

00:17:05.609 --> 00:17:09.750
I mean, the sheer size of
the icebergs is humbling.

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:13.050
And the ice fields, they
vibrate with movement

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:15.616
and sound in a way
that I never expected.

00:17:15.616 --> 00:17:17.490
That's what prompted me
to bring my recording

00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:18.910
equipment on my
more recent trips

00:17:18.910 --> 00:17:20.490
so I could bring
that back to you.

00:17:20.490 --> 00:17:24.420
And it's also why I decided to
expand the scale of my work--

00:17:24.420 --> 00:17:32.200
to give viewers that same sense
of awe that I had experienced.

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:34.570
The melting glaciers
in Greenland

00:17:34.570 --> 00:17:36.850
are one of the largest
contributing factors

00:17:36.850 --> 00:17:39.580
to rising sea levels,
which have already

00:17:39.580 --> 00:17:44.230
begun to drown some of our
world's lowest-lying islands.

00:17:44.230 --> 00:17:46.390
One year after my
trip to Greenland,

00:17:46.390 --> 00:17:48.910
I decided to fly to
the Maldives, which

00:17:48.910 --> 00:17:52.780
is the lowest and flattest
country in the entire world.

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:54.730
And while I was
there, I collected

00:17:54.730 --> 00:17:58.870
images and inspiration
for a new body of work--

00:17:58.870 --> 00:18:02.290
drawings of waves
lapping along the coast

00:18:02.290 --> 00:18:06.050
of a nation, a whole nation
that could be entirely

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:08.055
underwater within this century.

00:18:10.580 --> 00:18:12.560
While I was there
with my collaborators,

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:14.270
we shared the concept
of our project

00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:16.940
with children at the
Iskandhar Elementary School

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:20.180
at the nation's
capital called Male.

00:18:20.180 --> 00:18:22.250
And we basically
just invited them

00:18:22.250 --> 00:18:26.540
to document their
landscape as it transforms

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:28.910
throughout their lifetime.

00:18:28.910 --> 00:18:31.820
And hopefully that can
help to bring awareness

00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:34.520
to their island, which is
actually still very much

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:37.850
needed, surprisingly enough,
and also just help them

00:18:37.850 --> 00:18:40.940
kind of inwardly,
emotionally process what

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:44.920
is happening around them.

00:18:44.920 --> 00:18:47.710
Last winter, I had
the honor of serving

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:50.230
as the artist-in-residence
aboard the National Geographic

00:18:50.230 --> 00:18:53.180
Explorer in Antarctica.

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:56.710
I have traveled to
many stunning places,

00:18:56.710 --> 00:19:01.180
but Antarctica is just
in a category of its own.

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:05.020
The ice just like
radiated sapphire blue,

00:19:05.020 --> 00:19:07.082
as you can see in this
video, and it just

00:19:07.082 --> 00:19:08.320
took my breath away.

00:19:08.320 --> 00:19:10.720
It's what inspired
a whole body of work

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:14.110
that I just completed that
I worked on for the last 18

00:19:14.110 --> 00:19:16.750
months.

00:19:16.750 --> 00:19:21.640
And I'll just show you a time
lapse of one of those pieces.

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:22.830
It's called "Whale Bay."

00:19:22.830 --> 00:19:25.750
It was inspired by a place
called Whale Bay that's

00:19:25.750 --> 00:19:27.040
on the Antarctic Peninsula.

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:30.220
And the bay is situated
near a glacier that's

00:19:30.220 --> 00:19:34.160
calving icebergs into the sea
as all glaciers eventually do.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:37.690
But the wind and water
currents carry the icebergs

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:40.510
directly into the bay because
of where it's situated.

00:19:40.510 --> 00:19:42.850
And since the bay
is kind of shallow,

00:19:42.850 --> 00:19:45.520
the icebergs will scrape
against the sea floor

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:48.640
and become what's called the
grounded, which basically means

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:52.010
they remain there until
they've melted completely,

00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:55.210
which is a process that can
take years if the icebergs are

00:19:55.210 --> 00:19:59.070
large enough like this one.

00:19:59.070 --> 00:20:01.210
And bays that enclose
icebergs like these

00:20:01.210 --> 00:20:05.575
are called iceberg
graveyards, which to me just

00:20:05.575 --> 00:20:07.450
seems like a metaphor
for the bigger picture.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:12.540
I had the opportunity
to ride around

00:20:12.540 --> 00:20:15.670
this bay for two hours
in a small zodiac boat.

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:17.410
This is a video I took there.

00:20:17.410 --> 00:20:20.980
A zodiac is a little
rubberized like 12-foot boat.

00:20:20.980 --> 00:20:22.967
And you'll actually
start to see the iceberg

00:20:22.967 --> 00:20:24.550
on the right-hand
side come into view.

00:20:24.550 --> 00:20:26.008
That's the iceberg
from the drawing

00:20:26.008 --> 00:20:27.680
that you just saw me making.

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:29.840
It's from a slightly
different angle.

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:33.560
So if you don't recognize
it, it's not my fault.

00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:36.940
But yeah, we got to ride around
for two hours just weaving

00:20:36.940 --> 00:20:39.430
around the most
intricately-sculpted,

00:20:39.430 --> 00:20:42.580
glowing blue icebergs
I have ever seen.

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:44.800
I mean, the longer
that they stay there,

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:48.880
the more the water and the wind
sculpts these blocks of ice

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:52.450
into just otherworldly shapes.

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:55.670
And I shot like
thousands of photographs.

00:20:55.670 --> 00:20:58.520
At times, I had to just
force my camera into my lap

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:03.490
so I could simply be present and
take in the overwhelming beauty

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:04.760
of it all.

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:07.420
And so I hope that my
drawings, as much as you

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:11.350
can see on these screens, can
offer you a similar experience.

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:18.810
So this past October,
I had the opportunity

00:21:18.810 --> 00:21:21.660
to see Antarctica from a
whole different perspective.

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:25.830
NASA invited me to join them
on Operation Ice Bridge, which

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:31.000
is the largest airborne
survey of Earth's polar ice.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.580
We flew 12 hours
every single day

00:21:33.580 --> 00:21:36.650
that the weather permitted
on the DC-8, which

00:21:36.650 --> 00:21:40.180
has the most comprehensive
suite of instruments ever flown

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:44.110
on long-range flights,
including laser, radar,

00:21:44.110 --> 00:21:47.500
an infrared sensor, digital
photography, and something

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:52.150
called a gravimeter that
houses Einstein's brain.

00:21:52.150 --> 00:21:53.400
It measures gravity somehow.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:54.384
I don't know.

00:21:57.927 --> 00:21:59.260
It was an incredible experience.

00:21:59.260 --> 00:22:02.240
It was humbling to
witness the science team

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:05.200
and aircrew's dedication
to their seriously

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:07.510
hard and grueling work.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:10.480
And the data collected
provides crucial information

00:22:10.480 --> 00:22:11.830
about ice loss--

00:22:11.830 --> 00:22:13.930
basically, what the
melting of ice sheets

00:22:13.930 --> 00:22:18.070
could mean for sea level rise
and what the melting of sea ice

00:22:18.070 --> 00:22:22.110
could mean for the entire
global climate system.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:24.480
This year, the
Antarctic sea ice loss

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:26.850
has been particularly swift.

00:22:26.850 --> 00:22:29.100
We even had to make some
last-minute modifications

00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:32.250
to one of our flight plans to
account for the significantly

00:22:32.250 --> 00:22:34.380
diminished sea ice.

00:22:34.380 --> 00:22:36.860
When NASA measured its
extent for this time of year,

00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:39.900
it was at the lowest
level ever recorded

00:22:39.900 --> 00:22:43.110
in reliable satellite history,
which dates all the way back

00:22:43.110 --> 00:22:44.910
to 1979.

00:22:44.910 --> 00:22:48.690
And since that year,
since 1979, the planet

00:22:48.690 --> 00:22:52.920
has been shedding massive
amounts of sea ice annually

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:59.170
that equal an area larger
than the state of Maryland.

00:22:59.170 --> 00:23:05.410
The scale of this loss is
difficult to comprehend.

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:07.600
And similarly, my
sense of perspective

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:10.144
was completely warped
as we flew over the ice.

00:23:10.144 --> 00:23:11.810
And just to give you
an example of that,

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:15.760
this is a photo from one of our
flights over a glacier called

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:19.540
Land Glacier, and it covers
the equivalent of 54 football

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:21.470
fields in that photo.

00:23:21.470 --> 00:23:22.970
It's just, I mean,
it's crazy to me.

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:25.450
It looks like a little crumble
of ice on the sidewalk.

00:23:25.450 --> 00:23:29.080
But that little blue crack
is probably 100 feet wide.

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:34.930
So this past April,
I was actually

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:38.530
able to join NASA's Ice
Bridge team again on some

00:23:38.530 --> 00:23:41.320
of their arctic
missions, and we flew

00:23:41.320 --> 00:23:45.100
over ice sheets, sea
ice, and glaciers

00:23:45.100 --> 00:23:47.770
in arctic Canada and Greenland.

00:23:47.770 --> 00:23:51.910
And it was just totally
thrilling to fly--

00:23:51.910 --> 00:23:54.940
once again, only 1,500
feet above the ice.

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:57.220
The instruments need
to be 1,500 feet,

00:23:57.220 --> 00:23:59.849
so it's actually
pretty low for a plane,

00:23:59.849 --> 00:24:01.390
and you really get
to see the detail.

00:24:01.390 --> 00:24:03.730
And it was just
so exciting for me

00:24:03.730 --> 00:24:07.300
to compare the ice to
its southern counterpart

00:24:07.300 --> 00:24:11.020
but also just reconnect with the
science team and the aircrew,

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:14.590
and kind of chilling to
learn of some of their more

00:24:14.590 --> 00:24:18.610
recent discoveries such
as a giant crack that

00:24:18.610 --> 00:24:21.010
is forming in the
Petermann Glacier, which

00:24:21.010 --> 00:24:22.850
could in the future--

00:24:22.850 --> 00:24:24.940
this is a picture of the crack.

00:24:24.940 --> 00:24:27.050
So it could, if it
splits off the shelf,

00:24:27.050 --> 00:24:28.690
mean a new ice island--

00:24:28.690 --> 00:24:30.340
basically, a giant iceberg--

00:24:30.340 --> 00:24:33.690
that's twice the
size of Manhattan.

00:24:33.690 --> 00:24:38.460
Findings from this close to
a decade now long project

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:42.960
are numerous and some of
them mind-blowing to me.

00:24:42.960 --> 00:24:46.020
For instance, they
found a canyon larger

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:48.747
than the Grand Canyon under
Greenland's ice sheet.

00:24:48.747 --> 00:24:50.580
Just like, we had no
idea that it was there.

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:52.204
It was just hiding
under the ice sheet,

00:24:52.204 --> 00:24:54.510
bigger than the Grand Canyon.

00:24:54.510 --> 00:24:58.020
But the most significant
data from the project

00:24:58.020 --> 00:25:03.930
have shown that the entire West
Antarctic Ice Sheet has likely

00:25:03.930 --> 00:25:06.390
entered an unstable
state and might now

00:25:06.390 --> 00:25:09.780
be in irreversible decline.

00:25:09.780 --> 00:25:13.650
And although the timing of
that retreat is unknown,

00:25:13.650 --> 00:25:16.770
it's still a powerful
reminder that we've

00:25:16.770 --> 00:25:19.881
entered a new era with
significant changes

00:25:19.881 --> 00:25:20.505
on the horizon.

00:25:23.320 --> 00:25:28.240
Our president has already
begun to defund NASA's climate

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:29.470
research.

00:25:29.470 --> 00:25:33.520
And the lead scientist at Ice
Bridge, named Nathan Kurtz,

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:36.820
recently emailed the
team and I to say, quote,

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:39.550
"In these uncertain times,
it is vitally important

00:25:39.550 --> 00:25:41.500
that we reach the hearts
and minds of people

00:25:41.500 --> 00:25:44.620
around the world to communicate
the importance of the work

00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:46.490
that we are doing."

00:25:46.490 --> 00:25:49.390
So I just want to
thank you for having

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:52.240
this opportunity to share not
only their really important

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:55.180
mission, but also my own work.

00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:58.090
And I hope that you'll
spread it as much as you can.

00:25:58.090 --> 00:26:01.090
And it's just an
honor to speak to such

00:26:01.090 --> 00:26:04.180
an influential audience.

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:09.090
So when I was in Greenland
back in 2012, that first trip,

00:26:09.090 --> 00:26:13.560
I scattered my mother's
ashes amidst the melting ice.

00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:17.340
And now, she remains a
part of the landscape

00:26:17.340 --> 00:26:22.890
that she loved so much even
as it, too, passes and takes

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:24.910
on new forms.

00:26:24.910 --> 00:26:27.550
Among the many gifts
that my mom gave

00:26:27.550 --> 00:26:32.170
me was the ability to focus on
the positive rather than dwell

00:26:32.170 --> 00:26:33.520
in the negative.

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:36.520
And honestly, that
lesson has rarely

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:39.720
felt more necessary than now.

00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:43.280
And yes, it's become far more
challenging to stay positive,

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:46.930
since January especially,
but I'm doing my best.

00:26:46.930 --> 00:26:49.580
And I encourage
others to do the same.

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:53.470
And former Secretary
General Ban Ki-moon

00:26:53.470 --> 00:26:56.440
said at the most recent climate
change conference in Morocco

00:26:56.440 --> 00:27:01.090
that action on climate change
has become unstoppable,

00:27:01.090 --> 00:27:04.030
and he's absolutely right, and
those are the words that I just

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:05.620
keep reminding myself of.

00:27:09.980 --> 00:27:13.940
On our family travels, every
time that we came across

00:27:13.940 --> 00:27:17.847
a really spectacular view,
my mom would do this thing--

00:27:17.847 --> 00:27:20.180
and I apologize in advance
because I'm going have to get

00:27:20.180 --> 00:27:20.840
loud--

00:27:20.840 --> 00:27:23.620
she would go, oh my god!

00:27:26.270 --> 00:27:30.650
And that was a taste because
I sound exactly like her.

00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:32.630
But it was special.

00:27:32.630 --> 00:27:35.240
She saved it for only
the best of the best.

00:27:35.240 --> 00:27:37.700
And so it would
happen once, usually,

00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:41.690
maybe twice if we were lucky,
on a four-to-six-week trip,

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:43.310
on each four-to-six-week trip.

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:46.170
And so, every single time we
approached a really beautiful

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:49.010
view, my dad and my
sister and I would

00:27:49.010 --> 00:27:52.215
glance at her wondering if it
passed the "oh my god" test.

00:27:54.820 --> 00:28:01.600
I try to uphold her reverence,
her legacy of drawing attention

00:28:01.600 --> 00:28:05.320
to the beauty of
these remote places,

00:28:05.320 --> 00:28:09.166
and I try to embody her
resolve and intrepidness

00:28:09.166 --> 00:28:14.560
I am so utterly grateful for
the time that I had with her

00:28:14.560 --> 00:28:16.030
and also for the
time that we all

00:28:16.030 --> 00:28:18.760
have to appreciate
what is around us

